<HEADLINE>
FT  03 SEP 93 / Observer: Some sum
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Reassuring news from the Central Statistical Office yesterday, which reveals
that Britain's families were forking out 5.8 per cent more of their
hard-earned pennies in 1992 compared with the previous year, despite all
that recession doom and gloom. But take a look at the price of accessing
this little gem.
The 1992 Family Expenditure Survey report itself costs Pounds 24, a tidy 17
per cent more than last year. Seeing that the latest figure for the retail
prices index, whose weightings are calculated largely from this very survey,
was July's year-on-year increase of 1.4 per cent, the CSO seems to have a
slight statistical anomaly to explain away.
</TEXT>
