<HEADLINE>
FT  03 SEP 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Guess the year: it is a Friday in September and the programmes on Britain's
main television channels include Coronation Street, Dad's Army, Alas Smith
And Jones, Bruce Forsyth's Generation Game, What The Papers Say, and
Gardeners' World. No, don't be facetious, there wasn't any television in
1890. The answer, of course, is 1993: the schedule is today's.
As so often in the summer radio is a better bet. That burgeoning broadcaster
Neil Kinnock presents Pick Of The Week on Radio 4 (7.20). Radio 3 provides a
live relay of tonight's BBC Prom in which the Austro-Hungarian Haydn
Orchestra makes its Prom debut. Naturally enough they play a good deal of
Haydn: the chorus from his oratorio 'The Return Of Tobias', the short
cantata 'The Storm', and Symphony No 97 in C (7.30). In Science Now Alun
Lewis reports on the annual meeting of the British Association For The
Advancement Of Science (8.50 Radio 4).
Channel 4 begins another run of Paul Merton - The Series with the star of
'Have I Got News For You' once again installed behind the counter of his
kiosk (10.30).
</TEXT>
