<HEADLINE>
FT  03 SEP 93 / The sun also rises in Colindale: Neil Buckley finds
philosophy at the heart of Europe's first Japanese shopping mall
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IT IS not just a range of products from octopus tempura to kimonos that sets
apart the Yaohan Plaza, the first Japanese shopping centre in Europe, from
home-grown competitors.
For the Yaohan Corporation, creators of the Pounds 50m centre which
officially opens today in the somewhat unlikely location of Colindale,
north-west London, claims its business is underpinned by philosophical
teachings.
Mr Kazuo Wada, its chairman, is an adherent of Seicho no ie, or the Human
Enlightenment Movement which espouses beliefs combining elements of
Buddhism, Christianity and Shintoism, and emphasises the infinite potential
of people if they co-operate to create harmony. Yaohan's mission is 'to
serve customers all over the world with gratitude'.
It is certainly aiming to serve the shoppers of north London with products
they may never have seen before.
One part of the complex is a 60,000 sq ft retail development (the size of
the biggest UK food superstores) operated by Yaohan, including a complete
Japanese supermarket, and a 200-seat oriental food court selling everying
from sushi to Chinese dim sum.
For UK customers not sure what to do with miso (fermented bean paste, used
for soups or flavouring), wasabi (strong Japanese horseradish) or daikon
(large white radishes), there are recipe cards in English, and regular
classes in Japanese cuisine.
About 70 per cent of goods will be imported from Japan, although some
Japanese vegetables may be grown in Europe.
The other part of the complex is a 82,000 sq ft mall with units rented out
to tenants including Japanese bookshops, travel agencies, a beauty parlour
and an optician's, a London-Tokyo property agency and the UK's biggest
computer game centre, operated by Sega.
Yaohan's main target is London's 30,000-strong Japanese population. Mr
Toshio Tajima, UK managing director, says research has shown there are
10,000 Japanese families in its target area, each spending about Pounds
3,000 a year on their groceries.
Yaohan aims to pick up 50 per cent of that spending in its supermarket -
Pounds 15m a year. It also expects to pick up a fifth of the estimated
Pounds 30m spent on groceries by London's other Asian and Far Eastern
communities, or Pounds 6m.
The shopping mall is forecast to have an annual turnover of Pounds 19m,
making Pounds 40m for the whole complex.
The company hopes to attract not just the oriental population. 'We do see
ourselves as ambassadors,' Mr Tajima says. 'We want to introduce Japanese
culture to local residents - starting with food.'
Yaohan began in 1930, supplying hotels in the resort town of Atami, near
Tokyo. It started retailing in 1956 but decided in the early 1970s that high
opening costs and intense competition in Japan made it sensible to look
abroad.
A successful Yaohan store in Singapore in 1974 became the foundation to
create the biggest store chain in south-east Asia. It also operates stores
in the US.
If London is successful, it hopes soon to persuade French customers to swap
their crepes for okonomiyaki in Paris, and Germans to swap bratwurst for
sashimi in Dusseldorf.
</TEXT>
