<HEADLINE>
FT  03 SEP 93 / Labour challenges Patten to oppose VAT 'on learning'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LABOUR yesterday stepped up its efforts to exploit the government's
budgetary difficulties by challenging Mr John Patten, the education
secretary, to speak out against the extension of value added tax to books
and children's clothes.
Mrs Ann Taylor, shadow education secretary, said the extension of VAT to
books and journals would cost English universities more than Pounds 11m a
year and reduce sales of children's books.
'VAT on books and journals would be a wicked tax on learning, a punitive
measure, at the very time that we need to be making it easier for people to
obtain reading matter,' she said.
'Earlier this year John Patten told parents to read to their children each
day. I challenge him to follow that up now by stating clearly his opposition
to an increase in the price of books.'
Mrs Taylor said ministers were preparing to widen the VAT net in the
November Budget as part of the government's drive to reduce its Pounds 50bn
budget deficit.
Labour's campaign is intended to embarrass the government by drawing
attention to its manifesto promise not to extend VAT. This was broken in the
last Budget when VAT was imposed on heating fuel.
The opposition also hopes to encourage Conservative councillors to oppose
further extensions of VAT.
Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, will not decide whether to increase
indirect taxes until nearer the Budget. However, books and children's
clothing are regarded as unlikely targets.
Labour's attack on VAT is part of a wider campaign to force the government
to focus revenue-raising efforts on eliminating tax breaks such as UK
residence trusts and private health insurance.
Mrs Harriet Harman, a Labour economics spokeswoman, said: 'The government
has chosen to ignore all these things, which would have made the taxation
system fairer and closed these loopholes.'
