<HEADLINE>
FT  03 SEP 93 / 5m workers exceed 48 hours a week
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MORE THAN 5m people, one fifth of all men and women in employment, work more
than 48 hours a week, according to research published yesterday.
This ranks the UK third, after Greece and Ireland, in an European Community
league table according to a report in the Employment Gazette, the official
publication of the Department of Employment.
The department is fighting, in the European Court, the proposed EC
working-time directive which proposes that employees work a maximum of 48
hours a week, with a statutory minimum paid annual holiday entitlement.
The research shows that in all EC countries, except the UK, the majority of
those working more than 48 hours are self-employed or work for their
families.
