<HEADLINE>
FT  03 SEP 93 / Tory constituency heads give Fowler a warm welcome
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IT IS early days yet. But if yesterday's enthusiastic reception in
Manchester and Liverpool is repeated elsewhere, then Sir Norman Fowler's
tour of Conservative constituency associations has the makings of a rare
central office success.
A sprinkling of the 60 or so constituency heads who attended yesterday's two
meetings appeared thrilled to bits that the Tory party chairman had taken
the trouble to consult them about their views.
The only hiccup was the hotter than expected weather. 'It is rather warm up
here,' said Mr James Fuke, a regional campaign executive, confiding that
those meeting Sir Norman over tea in west Derby had their jackets off and
'none of the ladies are wearing hats'.
Sir Norman has earmarked much of the next two weeks for what has been billed
as a morale-boosting tour of Tory constituency associations in England and
Wales.
Part of the purpose is to explain what lies behind the sweeping changes in
the party's central organisation that have been set in train over recent
months and to explain aspects of strategy ahead of next year's local and
European parliamentary elections.
But the greater part of the gatherings will be devoted to listening to local
grievances after what is acknowledged to have been a tough year for the
party. Sir Norman's introductory speech to yesterday's meetings  - in a
region where the Tory vote held up well in the last general election -
lasted just 15 minutes.
Constituency heads yesterday were reluctant to go into the detail of what
was discussed but agreed his performance had been impressive.
'We all went away in good heart,' said Mr John Longworth, chairman of the
Altrincham and Sale constituency. 'We had an excellent exchange of views
both ways.'
Ms Lynn Pratt, head of Bury North, said Sir Norman had been 'very willing'
to listen to ideas in what was a 'positive, frank and open' discussion.
According to Mr Fuke, officials expressed 'a cross-section of views' on
whether Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, should impose further tax
increases in November as part of the government's drive to reduce the public
sector deficit, or concentrate on cutting spending.
