<HEADLINE>
FT  03 SEP 93 / Key unions reject TUC's peace formula
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE THREAT of a bitter row at next week's Trades Union Congress grew closer
yesterday after two unions rejected a peace formula.
This would have smoothed the return of the expelled electricians into the
TUC as part of the AEEU engineering union.
Both the Ucatt construction union and the TGWU general union voted at
yesterday's TUC general council against the plan to deal with alleged union
poaching of construction members. The council had previously endorsed the
plan by 25 votes to 12.
The AEEU executive council agreed yesterday by 12 votes to 8 to accept the
TUC plan. Mr Bill Jordan, AEEU president, said it was 'a step forward for
trade union unity'.
Under the deal, the AEEU has given the TUC an unconditional guarantee to
abide by its rules and procedures; agreed to settle outstanding issues
through TUC conciliation; and accepted all the TUC dispute awards rejected
by the electricians six years ago when they were expelled.
The final decision on whether to accept the formula for their return will
rest with the delegates at the congress. Even if the TUC votes to accept the
electricians, the AEEU must still obtain a 75 per cent majority of its
executive council in order to change its own affiliation rules.
The hardest part of the plan concerns construction. The TUC has told the
AEEU that it must stop recruiting or seeking recognition from employers in
building and civil engineering without consultation with other unions in the
industry.
Ucatt and the TGWU are concerned that under the plan the AEEU will not have
to disband its construction section. Mr John Monks, the TUC's incoming
general secretary, yesterday denied the proposed peace plan could breach the
new employment law.
However, from November 30 individual workers will be legally entitled to
decide which union they want to join. It will be illegal for unions to deny
membership unless their rule books explicitly limit recruitment to
particular sectors.
Employers are still negotiating recognition agreements with unions for
collective bargaining despite the increasingly hostile climate towards trade
unionism, according to a study published today in Labour Research magazine.
A survey among 13 of some of the largest unions shows they have signed 103
such agreements since 1988. These brought nearly 18,500 workers into
recognised trade unions. Forty-two of these, covering 11,320 workers, have
been reached in the past two years.
Over the same period 100,000 workers in 310 companies have lost
representation.
Labour Research. 78 Blackfriars Road, London SEI SHF. Pounds 2.40.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P8631 Labor Organizations.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>PEOP  Labour.
</TP>
