<HEADLINE>
FT  03 SEP 93 / Campaign against Thorp reprocessing funded by international
financier
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRONWEN MADDOX
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir James Goldsmith, the international financier, is funding a high profile
campaign against the Thorp nuclear reprocessing plant in Cumbria, Bronwen
Maddox writes.
The Goldsmith Foundation, controlled by Sir James, has paid for an Pounds
18,000 balloon, in the shape of a white elephant.
It has also put up the finance for the campaign run by WBMG, the
environmental communications group.
Sir James' office said last night that the financier confirmed 'that he has
been funding groups opposed to nuclear power over a number of years and has
been helping groups opposed to Thorp'.
WBMG, whose directors include Mr Pete Wilkinson, former director of
Greenpeace UK, and Mr David Gee, former director of Friends of the Earth,
said yesterday that it 'couldn't deny' the contribution from the Goldsmith
Foundation.
According to Mr Wilkinson, WBMG wants to spread debate about whether Thorp
should be licenced to start operation beyond the 'green' movement.
'We are putting both sides of the argument before the public - the balloon
is a floating question mark' he said.
The elephant, which has been floating over Wiltshire and Kent, will tour up
to October 4, when the current public consultation on Thorp ends.
</TEXT>
