<HEADLINE>
FT  03 SEP 93 / Plea bargain waters down BNL charges
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN FRIEDMAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MS JANET RENO, the US Attorney General, yesterday approved an unexpected
plea agreement that throws out nearly all the charges against Mr Christopher
Drogoul, the former Banca Nazionale del Lavoro Atlanta branch manager at the
centre of the long-running Iraqi loans scandal.
Mr Drogoul, who made Dollars 5bn of loans that helped to finance Iraq's
nuclear and chemical weapons programmes, was supposed to stand trial next
Wednesday, accused of a range of conspiracy charges, money laundering and
defrauding the Rome head office of BNL. If convicted, he would have faced a
term of life in prison.
Instead, yesterday, Mr Drogoul was allowed to plead guilty to two counts
involving bank regulatory violations and one count of wire fraud. The
justice department said it would seek a jail sentence of about five years.
Mr Drogoul will have a chance to argue in court at his sentencing hearing in
November that higher authorities, including Rome, knew of his Iraqi loans.
The charges Mr Drogoul agreed to plead guilty to yesterday involve filing
misleading reports to the Federal Reserve Board and accepting a financial
gift from a BNL customer in order to repair his home.
Ms Reno, who personally made the BNL case decision, said yesterday: 'We are
going to continue our efforts to determine if other wrongdoing occurred.'
When asked if that meant the Justice Department would pursue allegations of
criminal wrongdoing by former Bush administration officials, a spokesman for
Ms Reno said: 'Absolutely.' He added: 'The investigation continues and is a
very broad one and includes all the allegations that have been made.'
Mr Drogoul was originally indicted on 347 counts in February 1991. Last
month lawyers for Mr Drogoul issued subpoenas demanding testimony from
former President George Bush and former Secretary of State James Baker,
arguing that the BNL loans were merely part of a larger US covert programme
to aid Iraq. The handling of the BNL case has led to congressional demands
for a special prosecutor.
</TEXT>
