<HEADLINE>
FT  03 SEP 93 / British Gas faces curb on expansion: Ofgas says UK customers
must not pay for any losses abroad
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBORAH HARGREAVES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH GAS'S ambitious overseas expansion programme would be severely
curtailed under controversial plans put forward by the industry regulator.
Ofgas, the gas industry regulator, wants to put a 'ring-fence' around the
Pounds 1.2bn profits that British Gas makes from supplying household
customers to protect them from any costs associated with high-risk overseas
projects.
The regulator, which has presented draft proposals to the company, is
worried that UK domestic customers could end up paying for project failures
abroad. 'Rather than success abroad keeping the home fires burning, we're
worried that disaster abroad could put the home fires out,' said Mr Greg
McGregor, director of competition and tariffs at Ofgas, echoing British
Gas's current advertising campaign.
But Mr McGregor stressed that he had no reason to believe British Gas's
overseas projects would fail.
If agreed by the government, the move would deal a significant blow to the
company, which has looked to growth abroad as a way of increasing its
profits at a time when its UK business is being eroded by increased
competition.
The company has invested Pounds 1.5bn in other countries since its
privatisation in 1986 and plans to spend a similar amount over the next few
years.
British Gas said recently that the outcome of the Monopolies and Mergers
Commission inquiry would force the company to put greater emphasis on its
overseas interests. The commission recommended in its conclusions last month
that the company sell off its trading arm by 1997 and lose its monopoly over
household supply by 2002.
Mr Philip Rogerson, British Gas's finance director, said he had not seen any
Ofgas proposals. 'But if they're saying the whole of our UK cashflow should
be ring-fenced that would be the cause of grave concern to us,' he said. The
issue is likely to exacerbate the already tense relationship between British
Gas and Ofgas which resulted in the monopolies inquiry last year.
The publication of the monopolies commission's full 2,000 page report on
Monday will show that British Gas called for a complete revamp of
regulation.
Ofgas says its ring-fence plans, which were presented to British Gas in
draft form at the end of last week, are a direct result of the monopolies
commission report.
The commission recommended that the company separate all 'treasury
functions' between its respective divisions.
Mr McGregor said the company had nothing to fear from the ring-fence
proposals as long as its projects overseas were on a secure and viable
footing.
British Gas could continue to invest in overseas businesses if Ofgas's
proposals were adopted but it would need to fund more investment on a
project finance basis which could involve taking on more debt.
British Gas is involved in negotiating a giant gas project in Kazakhstan
which would involve investment of Dollars 3bn over 10 years. Mr Rogerson
said the company's overall cash exposure would be less than Dollars 3bn and
expected it could be provided on a project finance basis.
</TEXT>
