<HEADLINE>
FT  03 SEP 93 / Howard ready to privatise 10 more prisons
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A FURTHER 10 prisons in England and Wales are to be run by the private
sector to complete the first phase of the government's privatisation
programme, Mr Michael Howard, the home secretary, announced yesterday.
With two prisons privately managed already, this would bring to 12 the
number of prisons run by the private sector. Prisons of all types -
including maximum security prisons holding terrorists - will be included in
the programme.
Mr Howard said his aim in the first phase was to have around 10 per cent of
the 132 prisons run by private companies. This would create a viable private
sector of three or four companies competing with directly managed
establishments.
The government is also to investigate using private finance to build new
prisons. The Prison Service will invite bids from the private sector to
finance, design, build and manage a new prison on Merseyside and another in
south Wales. This will be one of the first fruits of the private finance
initiative launched last year to attract private capital for public sector
projects.
The announcement drew renewed attacks from the opposition, prison staff and
penal reformers. Mr Tony Blair, shadow home secretary, described the plans
as 'a diversion of time and energy from the real task of penal reform and
fighting crime'.
The Prison Officers Association, representing more than 25,000 officers,
warned of possible industrial action because of overcrowding and inadequate
staff as a result of government policies. One action being considered is to
refuse to accept new inmates into prisons, forcing their detention in police
cells.
The Howard League for Penal Reform said that commercialising prison
management weakened accountability to parliament. Mr Brendan O'Friel,
chairman of the Prison Governors' Association, said there were serious
doubts about the success of private sector involvement.
However, the announcement was welcomed by companies in the fledgling private
prison sector. Mr Jim Harrower of Group 4, which runs the Wolds remand
prison on Humberside, said the opportunity to win further contracts would
give the company 'critical mass' in the field.
The first five privately managed prisons will be newly built. The Wolds
prison and Blakenhurst prison in Hereford and Worcester have already opened
under private management. The contract to run the new Doncaster prison goes
out to tender later this month and the contracts for the Merseyside and
south Wales prisons will be let next year.
Details, Page 8
</TEXT>
