<HEADLINE>
FT  02 SEP 93 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow ignores further falls in
bond yields
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US SHARE prices ended mostly flat to lower yesterday, in spite of further
declines in bond yields, writes Patrick Harverson in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average finished 6.15 down at 3,645.10. The more
broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 eased 0.41 to 463.15, while the American
SE composite edged up 0.37 to 458.97. Once again the Nasdaq composite
outperformed other indices, rising 3.31 to a record 746.15. Trading volume
on the New York SE totalled 246.6m shares.
Trading remained directionless for the third straight day, with dealers
blaming the subdued mood on an unwillingness among investors to become
involved ahead of the long holiday weekend, although some were reported to
be readjusting their portfolios for the start of the new month.
Falls in foreign markets, and early declines in bond prices, set the tone
for a downbeat opening. The day's economic news also failed to lift
sentiment - the National Association of Purchasing Management's August
report showed that manufacturing activity stalled last month. Analysts were
particularly worried by the decline in the NAPM's employment index, which
led some to revise downwards their expectations for August payrolls, which
will be unveiled in tomorrow's monthly employment report.
The day's other economic news - in July personal income fell 0.2 per cent,
personal spending rose 0.4 per cent and construction spending declined 0.5
per cent - provided contradictory evidence of the state of the economy, and
was largely ignored. Although bond prices rallied later in the day, sending
yields to new record lows, equities did not react, and remained trapped in a
narrow trading range just below opening values.
Honeywell dropped Dollars 3 3/8 to Dollars 35 1/2 in volume of 1.5m shares
and Litton Industries put on Dollars  1/2 at Dollars 67 as investors reacted
to Tuesday's late news that a California jury had ordered Honeywell to pay
Dollars 1.2bn to Litton for patent violation. Honeywell later said it would
appeal.
AMR, parent of American Airlines, rose Dollars 1 to Dollars 68 on reports
that it was considering spinning off three of its divisions into separate
companies. The stock later succumbed to selling, however, and ended down
Dollars  1/4 at Dollars 66 3/4 .
On the Nasdaq market, leading technology stocks were mixed. Microsoft
advanced Dollars 1 5/8 to Dollars 76 3/4 and Sun Microsystems added Dollars
 7/8 at Dollars 27 1/8 , but Apple declined Dollars  1/2 to Dollars 26.
Internet Communications forged ahead Dollars 1 1/2 to Dollars 6 5/8 after
announcing a big improvement in second-quarter earnings.
Canada
THE Toronto market opened lower but gradually improved through the day to
close with a small gain.
The TSE 300 index was finally 6.2 up at 4,143.7 as rises led falls by 372 to
348. Volume came to 51.2m shares. Most of the sub-groups showed little
movement, with seven higher and seven lower.
Federal Industries said it will sell 7m 'A' shares at CDollars 6.65 a share
to underwriters. The underwriters have an option for a further 700,000
shares at the same price. The 'A' stock slipped CDollars  1/4 to CDollars 6
7/8.
</TEXT>
