<HEADLINE>
FT  02 SEP 93 / Money Markets: Still tight in London
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CONDITIONS IN the sterling money market remained extremely illiquid
yesterday, with discount houses and clearing banks failing to offer bills to
the Bank of England in the earlier rounds of trading, writes James Blitz.
For the second day running, the overnight rate for lending sterling in the
wholesale cash market came close to 8 per cent as liquidity in the system
remained tight. There was a daily shortage of Pounds 1.75bn, but by
lunchtime yesterday less than half of this shortage had been removed.
In the afternoon, Pounds 983m was removed via the provision of band 1 and 2
bills at the prevailing rates. But the Bank of England provided dealers with
an unusually large level of late assistance - or emergency funding - to the
tune of Pounds 700m.
The shortages that the market has experienced lately are nothing new. They
are partly due to the draining of wholesale funds that accom-panied the Bank
of England's recent gilt auctions. The authorities have returned some of
these funds in their regular operations, but it will take time for the
def-icit to be completely removed.
However, one market dealer yesterday reiterated a long-standing complaint of
London dealers: that the system is increasingly dominated by one or two
clearing banks who have built up a large stock of eligible bills in recent
years.
He said these banks can sometimes hold back from offering bills to the
authorities with the aim of pushing up the cost of overnight lending and
improving the state of their balance sheets.
For the time being, the Bank of England continues to stand by the advantages
of a system in which commercial banks are far more deregulated than they are
on the Continent
In Europe, the focus of attention was on the fall in French franc interest
rate futures as dealers took the view that French rates would not come down
quickly. The December Pibor contract ended 18 basis points down at 92.83.
The March 1994 contract shed 15 points to 94.02.
In the German market, call money declined sharply as the new month started.
It dropped from Tuesday's level of 7.75 per cent to as low as 6.85 per cent
yesterday after the Bundesbank allocated DM56.8bn of liquidity into the
market, against DM48.9bn of expiring facilities.
</TEXT>
