<TEXT>
London robusta COFFEE futures fought their way back into the plus column by
the close of trading yesterday after sustaining another sharp decline in the
morning. The November position slipped to Dollars 1,245 a tonne at on stage,
repeating Tuesday's Dollars 20 fall, before ending at Dollars 1,263, up
Dollars 2 on the day. The rally was attributed to a steadier performance in
the New York arabica market and continuing concern about availability of
good quality beans for immediate delivery. The latter factor was reflected
in the widening of the September/November premium by Dollars 7 to Dollars 75
a tonne. COCOA prices also ended off the lows, but still down on the day.
Stronger sterling was putting pressure on the market as the December
position fell to Pounds 824 a tonne. Later the price rallied to Pounds 829 a
tonne, down Pounds 3 on the day. At the London Metal Exchange the three
months delivery ZINC price slid below the Dollars 890-a-tonne mark on
speculative selling, but then held relatively stable. It closed Dollars 2,25
down at Dollars 887.25 a tonne. The GOLD price failed to hold yesterday's
move above Dollars 370 a troy ounce, closing in London at Dollars 369.75 an
ounce, down Dollars 1.55 on the day.
