<HEADLINE>
FT  02 SEP 93 / Commodities and Agriculture: Fuel shortage may halt Kazakh
harvest
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
KAZAKHSTAN MAY have to halt this year's harvest campaign because of severe
fuel shortages, the Itar-Tass news agency quoted the deputy head of
Kaznefteprodukt state oil company as saying, reports Reuter from Moscow.
Mr Igor Medvedev, an official at the Russian energy ministry confirmed that
big Russian oil companies had refused to send oil to Kazakhstan because of
debts of about Rbs87bn (Pounds 60m).
Kazakhstan expects a grain harvest of about 30m tonnes this year, down from
last year's record 32m. The republic had harvested 5.76m tonnes of grain by
August 27, up from 5.16m a year earlier.
</TEXT>
