<HEADLINE>
FT  02 SEP 93 / UK Company News: Charges deepen Osprey losses
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DON FARRELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AFTER CHARGING a Pounds 3.49m loss on discontinued operations Osprey
Communications incurred a pre-tax deficit of Pounds 4.25m in the 12 months
ended May 31.
The period is part of the new accounting year, which now ends on September
30. In the comparative period the loss was Pounds 336,000 after exceptionals
of Pounds 355,000.
During the period the group, which provides advertising and associated
services, sold the marketing services division to management for Pounds
2.1m, bought SMS Communications for Pounds 1.63m in cash and shares, and
raised Pounds 1.3m net via a rights issue.
On completion of those transactions Mr John French resigned as chairman and
chief executive and was succeeded by Mr Jack Rubins.
The new chairman said yesterday that negotiations were in hand for the
disposal of Rayner Holdings and Acute-Marketing and Communications, two of
the small regional subsidiaries, to their managements.
Provision had been made for the release of goodwill in the accounts.
Mr Rubins said despite the greater than expected trading loss - Pounds
384,000 from turnover of Pounds 21.9m - the balance sheet had been
substantially enhanced by the disposals and rights issue. At May 31 a pro
forma statement showed net assets of Pounds 636,000 - in the balance sheet
there were negative assets of Pounds 950,000.
The group was profitable in June and July, with the performance of SMS being
'particularly encouraging'. Mr Rubins said the group was beginning to make
progress.
Losses per share were 28.6p (2.03p) of which exceptionals accounted for
24.95p. To preserve trustee status an interim dividend of 0.1p is declared.
</TEXT>
