<HEADLINE>
FT  02 SEP 93 / UK Company News: Hanson spells out cost of US strike
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MAGGIE URRY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE US coal miners strike affecting some of Hanson's US coal mines could cut
the Anglo-American conglomerate's profits by between Pounds 60m and Pounds
80m in the fourth quarter of its current financial year which ends this
month. The cost would continue at a similar rate as long as the strike
continues at its current intensity, it emerged yesterday.
The forecast appeared in a letter to shareholders of Quantum Chemical
Corporation, the US group which has agreed to a bid from Hanson worth
Dollars 3.3bn (Pounds 2.22bn), including the assumption of Dollars 2.5m of
debt.
The letter calls for a special meeting of Quantum shareholders for September
30 (Hanson's year end) to vote on the merger. The vote requires a two thirds
majority of shares in issue.
In the letter Hanson said the strike, which had hit 20 of its Peabody
subsidiary's 22 mines and facilities, had cut profits by Pounds 29m in the
third quarter of its year.
It said talks between the coal operators association and the union had
recommenced on August 11, but there was no guarantee that these would lead
to an agreement by any particular date.
The letter also shows that if Quantum accepts a higher offer from another
bidder it would have to pay Hanson a Dollars 50m fee. This could deter other
potential buyers, the letter said.
Further, it says that nine officers of Quantum would share a lump sum
payment of Dollars 18.7m if the merger goes through. An option scheme would
be worth Dollars 11.9m to Quantum's executive officers and Dollars 1.64m to
its non-employee directors.
In the letter Quantum, which makes polyethylene and other chemicals, gives a
forecast of operating profits for 1993 to 1997, although warning that the
numbers could vary materially.
The profit projection shows operating profits of Dollars 105.3m in 1993
rising to Dollars 546m by 1997, with net income moving from a loss of
Dollars 102m in 1993 to a profit of Dollars 186.1m in 1997.
The projection is based on forecasts of polyethylene volumes and prices,
annual cost savings rising to Dollars 66m in 1997, and other factors
including the receipt of a Dollars 32.1m insurance claim by the end of 1993.
Hanson's shares fell 2 1/4 p to 257 1/2 p yesterday, although it has risen
from 222 1/2 p since June 30 when the merger with Quantum was announced.
</TEXT>
