<HEADLINE>
FT  02 SEP 93 / Tate &amp; Lyle issues profits warning: Tate shares fall
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MAGGIE URRY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SHARES in Tate &amp; Lyle fell 25p to 375p yesterday after the sugar and
sweeteners group said profits for the year to September 25 would 'fall short
of the 1991 level'.
Analysts cut profit forecasts from around Pounds 235m to about Pounds 220m
pre-tax following the announcement. Some also cut forecasts for 1994.
Tate said this year's results would still show 'a marked improvement over
those achieved last year', when it suffered its first trading reverse for 14
years.
In 1992 pre-tax profits dropped to Pounds 189.5m from Pounds 230.8m in 1991.
Analysts had expected a rebound above the 1991 figure in the current year, a
view reinforced by interim pre-tax profits up 20 per cent to Pounds 107.6m.
Tate said trading in its North American sweeteners businesses had been less
buoyant than expected in the second half of the year.
In North America, Western Sugar, which processes sugar beet, had
difficulties at a new molasses desugarisation plant. US government quotas,
introduced to reduce the amount of sugar on the market, had forced it to
hold higher stocks.
Low sugar prices hit margins at Tate's Domino sugar subsidiary, which
refines sugar cane.
AE Staley, which makes high fructose sweetener from corn, had recovered some
of the volume it lost in 1992, but prices had not risen as hoped, Tate said,
and margins fell. The industrial dispute at Staley was yet to be resolved
but would not have a material effect on profits. Floods in the mid-west had
cut production from some rivals but this was too late to benefit the 1993
figures.
Mr Paul Lewis, finance director, said the announcement had been made because
the group was seeing analysts later this week before annual results are
published in November.
Tate thought market forecasts were too high and decided to make a public
statement, following the London Stock Exchange's censure of London
International Group after it guided analysts to cut profit forecasts without
making a formal announcement.
Mr Lewis, who appeared surprised by the London stock market reaction, said
the statement represented a 'slight modification' to expectations, which
would not affect dividend policy.
Lex, Page 18
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Tate and Lyle.
