<PROFILE>_AN-DIBB8ACEFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930902
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  02 SEP 93 / Bifu opts against strike at Lloyds
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
FINANCE UNION Bifu today decided against launching industrial action over a
pay freeze and proposals for performance-related pay by Lloyds Bank.
Bifu members in Lloyds voted narrowly in favour of a series of one-day
strikes in a ballot that ran through August.
But the turnout was so low that union officials felt unable to authorise
industrial action.
Mr Rob O'Neill, assistant secretary, said: 'The message to the bank is
clear. Many staff are not happy with the bank's proposals, but are not
prepared to take industrial action. Rather than vote no in the ballot and
give the bank the impression that they are happy, they have stayed away.
He added: 'We are very disappointed. Lloyds are the most profitable high
street bank, yet they have imposed a pay freeze on staff.
'There is widespread concern in Lloyds over pay and that will not go away.
We're not ruling out another ballot in the future once Lloyds' plans on pay
become clearer.'
As well as a pay freeze this year, Lloyds says it wants to scrap
across-the-board increases and link future pay to staff performance.
A separate Bifu dispute over shift working at Lloyds London computer centre
continues.
</TEXT>
