<HEADLINE>
FT  02 SEP 93 / TUC urges Pounds 3bn training cash rise
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT should spend an extra Pounds 3.2bn on training and job
creation measures in its November Budget to cut unemployment, says the
Trades Union Congress in its submission to the chancellor published
yesterday.
In its proposals, under the catch phrase 'investing in all our people', the
TUC recommends that the government's training for work scheme should be
expanded by 180,000 to 500,000 places at a cost of Pounds 2bn in the next
financial year.
It also proposes that the government's pilot Workstart job subsidy scheme
should be developed with an extra 200,000 places at an added cost of Pounds
1.2bn. At present there are only 1,000 places in what is still an
experimental scheme.
The TUC believes the proposed job subsidy could be equal in amount to the
average cost to the exchequer of an unemployed person in lost taxes and
benefit payments.
It suggests an average subsidy of Pounds 115 a week.
It estimates that the removal of every 250,000 from the unemployment
register to full-time work would provide the Treasury with a direct net gain
of Pounds 2.2bn. The TUC urges Mr Kenneth Clarke to make no tax increases in
his Budget except on the top 1 per cent. It also opposes public spending
cuts and reductions in benefit entitlement as 'unfair, unnecessary and
counter-productive'.
The TUC argues that the large size of the public sector borrowing
requirement is not due - as ministers argue - to excessive public spending
but to the loss of tax revenues because of the recession. 'A restoration of
economic growth rates would have a dramatic impact on tax revenues and hence
on the overall PSBR,' it says.
The TUC calls for more targeted public investment on infrastructure
projects, a review of the financial rules governing public-sector industries
to allow in private finance, and a national training strategy.
</TEXT>
