<HEADLINE>
FT  02 SEP 93 / Supermarkets win Costco challenge go-ahead
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GUY DE JONQUIERES, Consumer Industries Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A HIGH COURT judge yesterday granted Britain's three largest supermarket
chains the right to an early hearing of their legal attempt to stop Costco,
a US-owned warehouse club, opening its first UK outlet in Thurrock, Essex.
The ruling, by Mr Justice Brooke, came as another council, Hertsmere in
Hertfordshire, approved in principle an application by Costco to open a
second outlet at Bushey, Hertfordshire.
J. Sainsbury, Tesco and Safeway are jointly opposing the decision last May
by Thurrock Council to award Costco planning permission for a warehouse as a
wholesale operation and not as a retailer.
Costco, which plans to sell goods ranging from baked beans to car tyres at
deeply discounted prices, says it is not a retailer because it will sell
only to club members.
But the supermarkets say Costco should be subject to planning rules similar
to those on retailers.
The supermarkets' legal challenge had not been expected to be heard for at
least 18 months, well after the planned opening of the Thurrock warehouse in
late November. Although Mr Justice Brooke set no date for a hearing he said
it was 'in the public interest' for the issues raised to be settled quickly.
He also denied Costco leave to appeal against his decision and awarded costs
against the company.
The hearing will be watched by many retailers as a test case with important
implications for competition in the industry.
The supermarkets, which have invested large sums in superstores, fear Costco
and other warehouse clubs would have an unfair advantage if they were not
required to operate from scarce and expensive retail sites.
Hertsmere council has agreed to authorise the construction of a Costco
warehouse on a non-retail site provided the company signs a legal agreement
restricting the range of products it sells.
The three supermarkets said they would not challenge the planned agreement
if they judged it to be sufficiently restrictive.
Since Thurrock granted Costco planning permission the department has issued
planning guidelines which advise local authorities to treat warehouse clubs
in the same way as retail outlets.
ASDA supermarket workers have voted overwhelmingly against strike action and
have accepted a 2 per cent pay increase.
Nearly 69 per cent of the 35,270 staff in the postal ballot responded - an
exceptionally high return, according to the GMB general union which
organised it.
</TEXT>
