FT  02 SEP 93 / Unions clash on building workers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PROPOSALS TO END an inter-union conflict in the construction industry that
threatens to disrupt next week's Congress in Brighton will be put to the TUC
general council today for its approval.
Mr John Monks, incoming TUC general secretary, is trying to resolve the row
about alleged membership poaching between the construction union UCATT and
the AEEU engineering and electrical union.
UCATT leaders are demanding an end to what they see as the AEEU's campaign
to recruit their members in construction.
They want the AEEU to dismantle its construction and building trades
section, insisting that this is the price the union must pay to bring the
electricians back into the TUC six years after their expulsion.
During their years outside the TUC the electricians - outside TUC rules on
inter-union relations - went on a membership recruitment offensive,
attracting workers from TUC unions into their own ranks.
Last night details of a proposed resolution of the dispute were not
disclosed.
AEEU leaders have argued that their union's construction section contains
many workers who were not recruited by the electricians from UCATT before
amalgamation.
