<HEADLINE>
FT  02 SEP 93 / Insurers attacked over house premium rises
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INSURERS HAVE come under attack from the Consumers' Association for
increasing house contents insurance premiums by 'staggeringly high amounts'.
The latest edition of Which?, the association's magazine, says the cost of
house contents insurance premiums has more than doubled since 1987, while
house buildings premiums have risen by more than half.
Insurance companies have 'bumped up the price of home insurance over the
past few years with swingeing increases that more than outstrip inflation -
partly to pay for their past blunders', says Which?
Mr Simon Hinde, a senior editor, says the increases are 'simply
unacceptable.
'Insurers have blundered badly over a long period and are making customers
pay for their mistakes. Instead of cutting costs and doing more to fight
fraud they're taking the easy way out - clobbering the consumer.'
Which? says insurers are 'worryingly reluctant' to cover homes which have
suffered from subsidence. Asked if they would insure a house underpinned one
year ago, more than three quarters of insurance companies contacted by
association researchers refused a quote or said they needed more
information.
Which? advises consumers to shop around by contacting at least one
intermediary.
It also says buyers should take care to ensure they are buying the right
amount of insurance and not to pay extra for cover they may not need.
The association urges consumers not to assume that an insurance policy
offered by their building society is necessarily a good deal for them.
Companies offering what Which? describes as 'best buys' include Direct Line,
for both claims and service on both buildings and contents, Frizzell, best
on service for contents policies, and Prudential for claims and service for
both buildings and contents.
Which? September 1993. Consumers Association, Subscriptions department, PO
Box 44, Hertford X SG14 1SH
</TEXT>
