<HEADLINE>
FT  02 SEP 93 / Arms export effort defies Scott probe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIMMY BURNS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE PUBLIC scrutiny to which Whitehall officials have been subjected by the
Scott arms-for-Iraq inquiry appears to have little impact on the way the
Ministry of Defence promotes British arms exports.
Yesterday senior MoD officials promoting a British army and navy equipment
exhibition which starts in Aldershot on Monday defended aggressive defence
sales promotion in militarily sensitive areas on economic grounds.
One official said: 'Defence exports don't make wars, they prevent them.'
Civil servants emphasised the need to promote defence exports which
accounted for an estimated 110,000 British jobs and defended the need to
observe client confidentiality.
It was also clear that they remain highly critical of what they perceive is
the unjustifiably negative image of government emanating from the Scott
inquiry. One senior official said: 'What I resent is the suggestion that the
British are conspiratorial, slightly dirty, and underhand.' He added that
the French continued to be far more unscrupulous in bending rules.
Since the arms-for-Iraq inquiry several MoD officials have been subjected to
detailed questioning by Lord Justice Scott and his counsel Miss Presiley
Baxendale QC about the extent to which government departments may have
circumvented guidelines restricting arms sales.
But their careers appear to have remained largely untarnished. One early
witness at the Scott inquiry, Mr Christopher Sandars, who helped oversee
defence sales in the 1980s, has recently been promoted from a post in the
cabinet office to under-secretary of state responsible for defence export
policy at the MoD.
The Scott inquiry resumes its public hearings after the summer recess on
September 13 with evidence being taken from Mr David Gore-Booth, the UK's
current ambassador to Saudi Arabia, who was previously under-secretary of
state responsible for the Middle East at the Foreign Office.
Three former Foreign Office ministers, Mr Timothy Renton, Mr David Mellor
and Mr William Waldegrave, are to give evidence in the following week. Lady
Thatcher is scheduled for December, prior to Mr John Major's appearance in
January.
</TEXT>
