<HEADLINE>
FT  02 SEP 93 / Greenpeace wins right to fight Thorp tests
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRONWEN MADDOX, Environment Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GREENPEACE, the environmental pressure group, yesterday won permission to
bring a High Court challenge against the government's decision to allow
radioactive testing of the Thorp reprocessing plant at Sellafield.
But the court also ruled yesterday that British Nuclear Fuels can begin
testing the Pounds 2.8bn plant's systems with uranium ahead of the two-day
review, which is set to begin on September 14.
However, Greenpeace said last night that it had secured an Appeal Court
hearing tomorrow for its application to overturn the decision to allow
testing. Greenpeace said that this could still prevent the plant becoming
contaminated with radioactivity as 'BNF told us after the hearing that
radioactive material will not be introduced into the plant for six days'.
Both sides claimed victory yesterday after the court hearing in the latest
round of the increasingly complex deliberations about whether the plant
should be allowed to start reprocessing used nuclear fuel.
BNF said: 'We welcome the news that Greenpeace have failed in their attempt
to halt uranium (testing).' Ms Bridget Woodman, Greenpeace's nuclear
campaigner, said: 'We are very happy to have won our application to seek
judicial review.'
Last week ministers told BNF that it could begin testing the plant with
radioactive material to save time if a licence is eventually granted. The
proposed tests will check radioactivity-measuring equipment and the part of
the plant that separates reusable fuel from the waste.
In refusing to block the testing ahead of September 14, the judge said that
he had been 'very considerably influenced' by BNF's estimates of its
financial loss and by Greenpeace's likely inability to compensate BNF for
that loss if BNF argued successfully that the delay was unjustified. Mr
George Newman QC had argued for BNF that if a 'stay' on testing had been
granted it could have cost the company up to Pounds 2m a week and put 700
jobs at risk.
But the judge also said that Greenpeace had 'an arguable case' for a
judicial review of the decision to allow testing.
Greenpeace is arguing that by allowing testing to go ahead the government is
prejudicing the decision on the plant's licence. BNF needs the same licence
to generate nuclear waste and emit radioactive discharges to carry out tests
as it would for full operation of the plant, Greenpeace claims.
If Greenpeace is successful on September 14, it will simply halt testing,
not the granting of a full licence. The government's decision on the future
of the plant is not due until after the current public consultation, which
is due to end on October 4. But ministers have already said that they are
'minded' to grant authorisation.
</TEXT>
