<HEADLINE>
FT  02 SEP 93 / Bosnian Moslems cut land demands
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURA SILBER and FRANCES WILLIAMS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BOSNIAN Moslems yesterday scaled back their demands for territorial
concessions in a move which could lay the ground for a possible agreement
between the three warring factions.
Bosnia's president Alija Izetbegovic tabled a proposal that his Moslem
republic should receive an additional 4 per cent of the 28 per cent already
allocated under the proposed partition. Previous Moslem proposals have
demanded at least 10 per cent more land.
The Bosnian Serbs were yesterday reported to have offered the mostly Moslem
Bosnian government full land access to the Moslem enclaves in eastern
Bosnia.
Serbian sources said Mr Radovan Karadzic, Bosnian Serb leader, had agreed to
give the Moslems a 1.8 mile-wide corridor linking the three enclaves.
But as the negotiations intensified, diplomats warned that the Serb leaders
had repeated that this would be their 'final concession' and the Moslem
delegation threatened to return home if their demands for additional land
were rejected.
'This demand is the minimum of minimums. If they (Serbs and Croats) reject
this, we are going home,' said Mr Mustafa Bijedic, Bosnia's ambassador to
the United Nations in Geneva.
Mr Muhamed Filipovic, a member of the Bosnian delegation, said his side was
demanding that the allocation of land to the Moslems be increased by 2 per
cent in the east and 2.8 in the west in order to improve on the maps which
leave his republic comprising seven isolated pockets.
Mr Izetbegovic is also asking for a land connection to the sea and the
Adriatic port of Neum.
However, citing 'historical' precedent, Mr Franjo Tudjman, Croatia's
president, has rejected Moslem demands on the grounds that giving up Neum
would isolate Dubrovnik, the resort on the southern Dalmatian coast, from
Croat regions.
As the three parties appeared to inch closer to a settlement, Mr Manfred
Worner, Nato secretary general, yesterday met Mr Boutros Boutros Ghali, UN
secretary general, to discuss the possible deployment of peace-keeping
troops.
In spite of hopes that the discussion might lead to a firm commitment about
the possible deployment of troops in the region, the discussions were held
under a total news blackout.
Nato officials yesterday denied that the silence reflected any political
disagreements. But with many diplomats remaining sceptical that the three
sides will reach a firm agreement quickly, both British and French
diplomatic sources stressed that they would not be prepared to commit any
troops until the there was a workable peace agreement.
Meanwhile, in an effort to broker a ceasefire between the Bosnian and Croat
forces, General Francis Briquemont, UN commander in Sarajevo, yesterday
travelled to Medjugorje to supervise talks between the two commanders.
A four-day ceasefire between the Croat and Moslem forces in Mostar is due to
run out this evening. However, a UN protection force spokesman in Zagreb
confirmed yesterday that there had been skirmishes throughout the day around
Mostar and across central Bosnia.
</TEXT>
<XX>
