<HEADLINE>
FT  02 SEP 93 / Newspaper price war stepped up by Murdoch: Times cut to 30p
as News Corp unveils satellite TV expansion package
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Rupert Murdoch's News Corporation last night widened Britain's newspaper
circulation wars by announcing that the price of The Times would be cut by
15p to 30p from next week. The price cut, the biggest of its kind in the
broadsheet market for decades, is aimed at reversing a declining circulation
which is affecting most of Britain's newspapers.
The announcement coincided with Mr Murdoch's launch of a multi-channel
package of satellite television channels in the UK as part of an ambitious
expansion package which includes a German TV deal and an 'open university'
in Asia.
The Times' price cut is likely to herald a period of intense competition
between broadsheet papers. Rivals, such as The Independent and The Daily
Telegraph, will be under pressure to follow suit. In a front-page editorial,
The Independent today appealed for its readers' support, accusing Mr Murdoch
of trying to drive it out of business. But none of the other broadsheets
would comment.
Mr Murdoch's move follows a successful 15p price cut for The Times in Kent
which increased sales by up to 15 per cent and a 5p cut in the 25p cover
price of The Sun, News Corp's leading UK tabloid, this summer. That resulted
in a 300,000 rise in sales.
A 30p Times, News Corp hopes, will take the paper from its current
circulation of about 370,000 to well above 400,000 and into second place in
the broadsheet market behind The Daily Telegraph. The immediate aim is to
win readers from The Independent, which has been going through difficult
times both financially and editorially.
Mr Murdoch's satellite TV package will make 18 channels available to UK
audiences by early next year. They will range in content from home shopping
to children's programmes. Most will be available only by subscription.
At a banquet in London last night to mark the launch of the Sky
Multi-Channels package, Mr Murdoch, News Corp chairman, said the age of the
media mogul was over. 'The consumer is in the saddle, driving the
telecommunications industry.'
He outlined a series of deals designed to ensure that News Corp would be
'part of this process of economic expansion'. They included:
A deal with British Telecom and Cellnet to explore digital 'super highways
of the future' with a 500-home experiment combining access to
telecommunications, TV shows, movies and specialist information.
A deal with Pro 7, the German broadcaster associated with the Kirch
Corporation, to develop pay television in German covering as many as six
channels.
The launch in Asia of a wide range of programming including an Open
University and educational channels using the Star satellite system. News
Corp recently bought control.
The launch of a second satellite sports channel in the UK.
A deal with Televisa of Mexico to produce 500 hours of multilingual popular
drama.
Completing the array of deals, News Corp last week spent Dollars 12m (Pounds
8m) on acquiring a small electronic publishing company, Delphi Internet
Services, which can handle electronic newspapers.
Meanwhile, Ms Ann Clwyd, shadow heritage secretary, called on the Monopolies
and Mergers Commission to investigate 'News Corporation's penetration of
this country's mass media'.
Sky channel package launched, Page 9
Letter, Page 16
Editorial Comment, Page 17
</TEXT>
