<HEADLINE>
FT  02 SEP 93 / Swan Hunter loses Pounds 50m order from Oman to French
shipyard
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WHITE and CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PROSPECTS for Swan Hunter, the struggling Tyneside warship builder, have
suffered a further blow with the loss of a crucial Omani order to French
competition.
The Cherbourg shipyard, Constructions Mecaniques de Normandie, said it
signed a firm contract yesterday to build three large patrol craft for
Oman's navy. The contract, worth about Pounds 50m, is expected to lead to
orders for up to five more vessels of the same type.
CMN also disclosed that it is among the companies which have expressed a
tentative interest in buying Swan Hunter.
The Tyneside shipyard, in receivership since May, was counting on winning
the Omani order to enhance its attractiveness to potential buyers. It now
has no shipbuilding orders on its books beyond the completion of work on
three Type 23 frigates for the Royal Navy.
Failure to win the Omani order has set back hopes of selling the company as
a shipbuilder. Union officials said it was likely to cost 100 more jobs from
a workforce of 1,700, already cut by 700 since May.
Joint receiver, Mr Gordon Horsfield of Price Waterhouse, said the news was
'obviously a disappointment' although not unexpected. He indicated that Swan
Hunter was unlikely to win orders of this type until a buyer was found for
the yard. Mr Alastair Balls, chief executive of Tyne and Wear Development
Corporation, said he feared the lost order would have a 'domino effect'.
CMN, which employs 500 people, is the sole shipbuilding interest of Soffia,
a French-owned construction group. Mr Pierre Belmer, CMN spokesman, said the
company had secured orders for a number of vessels in recent months. CMN had
spare capacity in Cherbourg, but had an expansion-minded management.
Mr Belmer said CMN would be in a position to take a decision on Swan Hunter
at the start of 1994, although any deal would be for part of Swan Hunter,
not for the company at its present size.
</TEXT>
