<HEADLINE>
FT  01 SEP 93 / Survey of Africa - A continent at stake (19): Dancing with
the dead at the Starlight - Journey to the heart of an anguished continent /
Nicholas Woodsworth travels from Bagamoyo, once the terminus of a busy slave
trading route, to the Great Lakes - retracing the paths trodden by those in
bondage in the 18th and 19th centuries
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NICHOLAS WOODSWORTH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THERE is not much left of Bagamoyo these days. It has become once again what
it was in the beginning, a somnolent backwater lost on a low coast at the
end of a bad road.
Campaign charts of a lost battle, maps of mould and lichen grow large on the
walls of imperial buildings in ruin. Wooden stick ribs protrude from the
sides of crumbling mud huts. Green bush and tropical lethargy encroach
everywhere. Even chickens peck languidly in Bagamoyo. On the afternoon I
arrived, the place hardly looked like a signpost pointing the way to the
heart of Africa.
But time, aided by heat, humidity and termites, has simply covered over the
traces of the past. Once Bagamoyo was the terminus of a busy Arab slave
trading route stretching 700 miles into the interior. 'Lay down your heart'
is the Swahili meaning of the word Bagamoyo, and in the phrase lies millions
of men's, an entire continent's, anguish.
But Bagamoyo did not only export African tragedy to the rest of the world;
it was also the conduit that brought the rest of the world, and many of its
tragedies, to Africa. In the mid-1800s Richard Burton, John Speke, Henry
Stanley, James Grant, all celebrities of the Victorian age, passed through
here, using age-old slave routes to rediscover and remake a continent. Near
the beach at Bagamoyo, over the door of a small weather-beaten church, is
nailed a sign honouring the passage of that greatest of explorers, David
Livingstone.
'I beg to direct your attention to Africa,' Livingstone addressed Cambridge
University in 1857. 'I know that in a few years I shall be cut off in that
country, which is now open. Do not let it be shut again] I go back to Africa
to try to make an open path for commerce and Christianity; do you carry out
the work which I have begun.'
We have, in a manner of speaking, carried out that work. Within a few years
Livingstone's penetration of Africa had become the rape of Africa. The
continent was transformed not by idealism, but by the steam engine, quinine
and the Maxim gun. Its own evolutionary patterns shattered, Africa was
co-opted into an imperfect imitation of a world that over-rode it.
Like a fastidious gentleman with desires satisfied and composure regained,
the world a century and a half on seems reluctant to continue the
relationship or consider too deeply the results. War, famine, debt, disease,
corruption, over-population, mismanagement, social breakdown and a hundred
other illnesses taint and exhaust the former object of its attentions.
Bagamoyo slumbers, a symbol of a pathway once open but now, as Livingstone
feared, at risk of closing down. The 'dark continent', once a romantic
mystery that demanded investigation, may finally become a reality no one
wants to know about. Bagamoyo is as good a place as any to contemplate its
future.
Dar es Salaam
I was not able, as I had intended, to catch the train that leaves from Dar
es Salaam and snakes slowly westwards across 700 miles of stunted, dusty
bush. One hundred and fifty years ago this was the route that led towards
central Africa and that holiest of Victorian grails, the source of the Nile.
Today the route remains almost as haphazard, and few overland travel
itineraries work out as planned.
I had to abandon the wheezing Peugeot bush taxi I had hired for the bumpy
trip from Bagamoyo to Dar, leaving it immobilised in a cloud of radiator
steam. I had to abandon too the patched-up bus that followed some time
later, leaving it raised forlornly on jacks. Can high-tech save the
continent? A blond Scandinavian in a shiny new aid agency Landcruiser saved
me, but me alone. I left my fellow bus passengers by the dusty roadside,
waiting, as all Africa sometimes seems to wait, for something to come along.
But not even imported technology allowed me to make my train - it had left
an hour before I finally reached Dar. Could I catch a fast bus and meet the
train at an onward station? It was not that easy. Tanzania's roads are
atrocious, so badly maintained they strangle the economy and so dangerous
that public buses are prohibited from using them at night.
I used what only the privileged can use to make life work in Africa - money.
For Pounds 18 - six weeks wages for a Tanzanian civil servant - I had a
privately hired, 26-seater bus rush me, its solitary passenger, 125 miles
through the darkness to the next train stop at Morogoro. With a little money
in Africa even mediocre men can become special men. It is what many whites
have always enjoyed.
Morogoro
Like the roadside villages I passed through that evening, the Morogoro
railway station at midnight was inky black, its platform a dark void
pin-pricked here and there by the flickering flames of kerosene lamps.
Drought here means more than parched fields; with hydro turbines silent, it
also means little power or electric light.
What does one do when the conveniences of modern life fail, when systems
break down, reserves are exhausted, ambitious plans come to nothing? In this
part of the world there is often little alternative - people simply bear
with it. In the dark I picked my way over a platform thick with sleeping
bodies bundled in blankets and as still as corpses, and settled down. What
does one do when finally opportunity presents itself? On a continent where
people are many and services few, one scrambles. When the train finally
pulled in the corpses sprang to life, bellowing and bumping blindly in the
night, everyone trying to get bags and bundles through doors and windows
before everyone else. The carriages may be over-crowded, the conductors
bullying, the toilets smelly, the dining car less than epicurean, but when
the choice is one of poor service or no service at all, there is little
dickering.
Tabora
Eighteen hours and some 400 miles later, the train passed through Tabora and
I got off. In their search for the Nile, Stanley, Livingstone, Burton and
Speke all found rest and uncertain hospitality here. From the 1820s Tabora
flourished as an Arab town, an inland centre for the depredations of
expatriate traders.
Slavery aside, things have not changed greatly today. On Tabora's dusty
streets I met Pyara Sokhi, a Sikh entrepreneur who has broken with the
town's small but powerful Asian community. Over a feast of curry in
celebration of Guru Nanak's birthday, Sokhi told me of his fears for
Tabora's future. In a vast, impoverished region where Arab, and now Indian,
interests maintain a firm grip on commerce, an African-run economy has
failed to get off the ground. Tanzania's new free market has made wealthier
those who were already wealthy.
African Tabora is foundering. I had thought that putting up for three days
with the mud-brown water and wriggling insect larvae that dribbled out of
the tap in Tabora's dilapidated Railway Hotel bad enough. I was not prepared
for the depressing year-in, year-out reality that Pyara Sokhi introduced me
to.
At the Tabora Boys' Secondary School, once an educational showpiece, I
watched Danish aid workers fit new plumbing into old buildings. There is so
little public money for education that Danida has had to undertake the
refurbishment and maintenance of public schools throughout the country.
Julius Nyerere, the architect of Tanzanian socialism, boarded and studied in
this school 45 years ago; today, his experiment in tatters, he would find
there are not even enough desks or beds to go round. In the town library
most books date from the 1960s. Computers are merely a rumour.
In Tabora's Kitete Hospital, the largest in a region of 18m people, a
shortage of Tanzanian staff has been bridged only by the voluntary services
of an eight-man medical team from China. The medicines are Chinese, as are
the operating theatre and technical equipment. Patients double up in beds.
There is no blood bank, no dependable electrical supply, and the water that
comes from the taps, when it comes at all, is the same mud-brown. I watched
a young child dying from third degee burns. Somewhere in the post, a doctor
told me, a grafting scalpel was on its way from China; it might or might not
arrive in time.
Chomachankola
In 1858 John Speke, the Victorian explorer of the Nile's source, swung north
from Tabora and crossed a burning and inhospitable plain to the green shores
of Lake Victoria. I did too, hitching a ride with Phil Riddell, a United
Nations irrigation specialist.
Bright and energetic, Riddell is typical of the best of a new generation of
expatriate specialists on the continent. Since the first aid efforts of the
1960s lessons have been learned and plans scaled down to better suit
Africa's abilities to make them work. Riddell remains enthusiastic about his
work; Africa is vital, he believes, to the world's long-term food
strategies.
But as we bounced along a dirt track towards a new irrigation project at the
village of Chomachankola, he acknowledged that he wrestles, often
unsuccessfully, with problems spared much of the rest of the world. Riddell
has worked in Asia, where technology and foreign aid has been grafted to
firmly established productive systems. He is also familiar with the Middle
East, where new systems have been tailor-made in technologically virgin
territory. Africa, he says, is more difficult than either.
Here local technology is not sophisticated. But in the past at least, he
said, it was substantial and assured survival. Now, because of population
pressures, environmental change, domestic political policies and global
economics, old techniques are no longer viable. They are also difficult to
adapt. Technology is inseparable from the history of the people who use it;
on a continent forcibly prised from its past, it has no firm base to build
on.
Great problems are made up of a series of little problems. At Chomachankola,
Riddell was happy with progress being made on the low-tech, gravity-fed
irrigation project there. But when I last saw him at Mwanza on Lake Victoria
a few hours later he had forgotten the dream of global food supply; he was
back at the cutting edge, arguing with a drunken port official, who for a
bribe had sold his reserved car space on a ferry west to the next aid
project. There is a more crucial factor to to aid than technology, Riddell
admitted. It is the human factor. I boarded my own ferry north to Uganda.
Kampala
I enjoyed dancing with the bar girls of the Starlight Nightclub. They are
vivacious - full of energy and the sensual enjoyment of music and movement.
But they also made me sad. They are survivors in a decimated country. What
Idi Amin began, Aids has continued. Soon, many of them too shall be gone. I
tried not to think that evening that I was dancing with the dead.
But Kampala is an African city that shows one of Africa's greatest
attributes - resilience. Here everyone is a survivor of not just Aids, but
of two decades of violence and megalomaniacal government. Yet Ugandans show
a will to rebuild their lives. The streets of Kampala may still be
down-at-heel and battle-scarred, but the crowds that throng them have an
insuppressible vitality and lack of rancour.
In the Nakasero market I bought a souvenir made from throw-away bits of
western technology. It is a small lamp made of an inverted light bulb fitted
with a wick and mounted on the lid of a Danish butter tin. Filled with
kerosene, such lamps bring light to a country where 90 per cent of homes are
without power. It is a simple re-application of means to needs. For me it is
a symbol, full of hope, of Africa's capacity to find ways out of disaster.
Jinja
By kamikaze-piloted mini-bus, the town of Jinja lies a hair-raising two
hours from Kampala along the shores of Lake Victoria. For me it was the end
of a 10-day journey; for the Nile it is the beginning of a 2,000-mile trip
that ends in the Mediterranean. Jinja lies in lush countryside amid rolling
fields of coffee, maize, tea, and bananas. It is a place of such beauty and
fertility that it is hard to believe things could ever go far wrong.
Certainly, when he first walked here beside the turbulent and fast-flowing
Nile Speke could not have imagined how far wrong the African future could
go. Nor could the prosperous Asian community that until the 1970s made this
a prosperous industrial centre.
For 20 years Jinja has been a decaying town, its foreigners expelled, its
factories expropriated, its once-sumptuous villas and mansions run to ruin
by the poor families that camp out in them. It is a place that might have
gone the way of Bagamoyo. But Jinja is slowly coming alive again. Former
non-indigenous owners and businesses are trickling back, encouraged by a
government that now believes the benefits of foreign involvement outweigh
the disadvantages.
Do they? From the point of view of most westerners there would seem to be
little gain. Even 10 days of casual travel makes Africa appear to be a
continent adrift, its problems intractable, its potential unrealisable. How
must it look to the foreign banker, businessman, or diplomat?
A century ago the Victorians found that African exploration raised more
questions than it answered. Today we are explorers of new African frontiers,
and the answers are even harder to come by. Is a revival like Jinja's,
fairer and more equitable to African interests, realistically possible?
Is the continent doomed to become one vast Bagamoyo? Our idealism has been
much tempered since Livingstone first directed our attention to Africa. A
short journey here makes his warning seem now almost too late. But perhaps
not - Africa is inextricably involved with the rest of the world. What began
long ago with Arab traders continues today with Chinese doctors, Indian
businessmen, Norwegian aid workers, British engineers. Once discovered,
Africa will not go away.
</TEXT>
