<DOCNO>FT933-5764</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-DIAB3AGGFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930901
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  01 SEP 93 / Survey of Africa - A continent at stake (8): Devaluation is
overdue - CFA
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EDWARD BALLS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IN PUBLIC, World Bank officials bite their lips at the mention of the CFA
franc zone, and the severe economic difficulties of its 13 west and central
African member states, In private, they tear out their hair.
Fixing their currencies to the French franc and to each other was once a
guarantee of low inflation and economic stability for the members - Benin,
Burkina Faso, Cameroon, Central African Republic, Chad, Congo, Equatorial
Guinea, Gabon, Ivory Coast, Mali, Niger, Senegal and Togo. Now this monetary
union is transmitting a recession across the region.
Since 1985, the combination of declining commodity prices, lax domestic
fiscal and monetary policies and the appreciation of the French franc
against the US dollar mean that the CFA group have suffered a huge real
exchange rate appreciation of more than 30 per cent as the chart shows. The
result was an immediate and sharp loss of competitiveness for exporters from
the CFA zone. By 1991, average wages in Senegal, for example, had risen as a
proportion of average income to three times the level in Ghana and six times
that of Indonesia. The CFA franc is now about 30 per cent overvalued.
This loss of competitiveness delivered a downward deflationary spiral in the
CFA zone, fed by deflationary macroeconomic policies as countries tried to
control the fiscal deficits that this shock opened up. Real output per head
in the CFA countries had risen by around 2 per cent in the first half of the
1980s. It fell by an average 5 per cent a year between 1986 and 1991.
Neither the French government nor the CFA members are willing to recognise
either that the French franc-CFA parity, unbroken since 1948, is at the
heart of the crisis or that a substantial CFA devaluation may now be the
only way to preserve the zone. Instead, the CFA countries have tried to
correct their severe external and fiscal imbalances through fiscal austerity
and attempted wage restraint without recourse to devaluation. Most of the
group have tried to adopt World Bank-style adjustment programmes in the late
1980s.
The results have been disastrous. Battling against an uncompetitive exchange
rate, growing capital flight, a powerful and a restive civil service, most
of the CFA countries have been unable to meet the demanding macroeconomic
and structural targets that internal adjustment demands. The poor have
suffered at the expense of the urban elite able, with the help of aid flows,
to preserve their purchasing power. In Niger and Chad, the civil service
wage bill exceeds total tax revenue.
The result is what bank officials call a 'silent crisis'. Inflation is low,
there are goods in the shops and civil servants are still being paid. But
poverty is rising, the infrastructure decaying: without devaluation combined
with tight control on civil service salaries, the crisis will deepen.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>XMZ  Africa.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
