<PROFILE>_AN-DIAB3AGDFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930901
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  01 SEP 93 / Survey of Africa - A continent at stake (6): Better chance
than most - Zimbabwe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TONY HAWKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ZIMBABWE climbed, reluctantly, aboard the structural adjustment bandwagon in
1991, largely jettisoning the ideological baggage that so constrained the
economy during the 1980s. The five-year programme started badly, primarily
due to the worst drought in living memory, global recession and high
interest rates.
Few of the programme's quantitative targets are likely to be met by 1995.
Real GDP, programmed to increase 25 per cent over the five years, will have
fallen some 2 per cent by the end of this year, with the result that incomes
today are around their levels of 20 years ago. Even if all goes well over
the next two years, it will take conceivably until the turn of the century
for income per head to regain its 1990 levels.
Initial programme-funding targets have proved wildly optimistic and the
government has been forced to turn to the International Monetary Fund for an
extended structural adjustment facility, as well as stepping up its reliance
on aid.
Fiscal targets have been missed - for which the drought is blamed - and last
year's budget deficit of 11.3 per cent was well above the 6.6 per cent
programme target. Exports, which by 1993 were supposed to have reached some
Dollars 2,150m, are languishing around Dollars 1,500m, and will fall
substantially short of the 1995 target of Dollars 2.6bn - the World Bank's
forecast, of tobacco exports doubling by the late 1990s, being a classic
example of confusing a short-term blip with a long-term trend.
In the past six months, the pace of reform has quickened, though
heel-dragging continues in the parastatal sector.
On the positive side, finance minister Bernard Chidzero, in a remarkably
opaque budget presentation in July, promised to halve the budget deficit to
5.4 per cent of GDP this year, by keeping spending growth to half the
inflation rate while revenue rises more than a quarter.
Investment is gradually - grudgingly - being liberalised, as are exchange
controls. Individuals may now hold foreign currency deposit accounts in
Zimbabwe banks, repatriating 'flight capital' on a no-questions-asked basis.
In mid-year, Mr Chidzero opened a window to portfolio investment,
guaranteeing free remittability of dividends and profits to foreign
investors who buy shares on the Zimbabwe Stock Exchange.
The main obstacle to foreign investment remains exchange control, which
discriminates against the country's traditional - and loyal - investors, who
were in Zimbabwe before independence in 1980. Trade is being liberalised,
with exporters allowed to retain half their export earnings - and this will
increase to 60 per cent at the end of the year - and a further 20 per cent
of imports on open general licence.
In July, too, important moves to liberalise agricultural marketing were
announced, and a commodity exchange now operates out of Harare, trading in
the main agricultural exports. But because there has been more pain than
gain, so far as the man in the street is concerned, the Economic Structural
Adjustment Programme is extremely unpopular.
With elections scheduled by March 1995, some slippage in implementation
seems more than probable. The politically-driven, and very popular, land
designation programme - by which government can compulsorily acquire
commercially-owned farmland for resettlement purposes - is incompatible with
some of the government's more progressive policies designed to attract
foreign investment.
In the final analysis, Zimbabwe has a better chance than most of breaking
the African mould and making a success of economic reform. Should it fail,
it will have much to do with institutional and political shortcomings, and
the over-indulgent attitude of some donors, specifically the World Bank.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>ZWZ  Zimbabwe, Africa.
</CN>
