<PROFILE>_AN-DIAB3AGCFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930901
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  01 SEP 93 / Survey of Africa - A continent at stake (4): Adjustment
abandoned - Nigeria
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TONY HAWKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SUCCESSFUL structural adjustment in Nigeria, the region's second largest
economy after South Africa and its most populous nation, would have created
the positive demonstration effect the continent needs so desperately. But it
was not to be.
A year after seizing power, in August 1985, General Babangida's military
administration launched a bold reform, unpopularly known as SAP (Structural
Adjustment Programme). The naira was devalued 66 per cent, import licensing
was abolished, tariffs were partially restructured, most prices were
deregulated, a privatisation programme was launched and monetary reforms
introduced. But the follow-through was weak; within 18 months, growing
public opposition to some of the measures, spearheaded by those who had lost
their preferential access to foreign currency, import licences and other
'rents', forced the government to back down.
With hindsight, the reflationary 1988 budget can be said to have marked the
end of effective reform. Nigeria's IMF programme began to collapse, and by
mid-1993 the country's arrears on external debt and trade payments were put
at more than Dollars 6bn. If failure could be attributed to a single factor,
it would have to be the military's inability to control public spending.
Substantial amounts of oil revenue - estimated at 200,000 barrels a day -
were siphoned off into 'off-budget' accounts and never accounted for.
Revenue-gathering efforts were stunted by the government's refusal to tax
domestic fuel consumption realistically and by massive evasion of border
taxes on imports. With a narrow revenue base substantially reliant on oil,
the budget deficit over the SAP period from 1986 averaged 7.7 per cent,
compared with 7 per cent in the pre-adjustment period.
SAP had its positive aspects, notably a distinct culture change within
Nigerian business: there is no support for a return to import licensing and
direct controls. In agriculture, food crop production went up 60 per cent
and export crops rose almost 45 per cent. Manufacturing saw strong growth in
textiles, with output more than doubling during 1986-89, having fallen 40
per cent between 1981 and 1986. Privatisation fell short, with 68
parastatals being fully or partially privatised by 1992, compared with a
target of 111 enterprises.
One central lesson is that, even with a 'big bang' approach, as in 1986-87,
adjustment cannot work unless the momentum of reform is maintained in
several different key areas simultaneously. When it came to the crunch in
1988, the political will was not there, and the country is now in crisis.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>NGZ  Nigeria, Africa.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9311 Finance, Taxation, and Monetary Policy.
    P9611 Administration of General Economic Programs.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>GOVT  Taxes.
    CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
    ECON  Economic Indicators.
</TP>
